revision.text:
{{Refimprove|date=June 2018}} In [[Intelligence (information gathering)|intelligence]], '''assets''' are persons within organizations or countries being spied upon who provide information for an outside spy.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Appel|first1=Edward|title=Recruiting and Operating Counterintelligence "Assets"|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/spy/counter/recruiting.html|website=www.pbs.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=INTelligence: Human Intelligence|url=https://www.cia.gov/news-information/featured-story-archive/2010-featured-story-archive/intelligence-human-intelligence.html|website=www.cia.gov}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Ekpe|first1=Bassey|title=The Intelligence Assets of the United Nations: Sources, Methods, and Implications|url=https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/08850600701249709|website=tandfonline.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=S|first1=Ben|title=Intelligence Assets: What is an intelligence asset?|url=http://www.intelligence101.com/intelligence-assets-what-is-an-intelligence-asset/|website=intelligence101.com/}}</ref> They are sometimes referred to as agents, and in law enforcement parlance, as confidential informants, or "CIs" for short.
There are different categories of assets, including people who:
* Willingly work for a foreign government for ideological reasons such as being against their government, but live in a country that doesn't allow political opposition. They may elect to work with a foreign power to change their own country because there are few other ways available. * Work for monetary gain. Intelligence services often pay good wages to people in important positions that are willing to betray secrets. * Have been blackmailed and are forced into their role. * Do not even know they are being used. Assets can be loyal to their country, but may still provide a foreign agent with information through failures in information safety, such as using insecure computers or not following proper [[Operations security (OPSEC)|OPSEC]] procedures during day-to-day chatting.
==See also== *[[Vetting]]
