[[Image:Monument National.jpg|thumb|The Monument-National in 2008]] [[File:Tombola au parc Sohmer Montreal.jpg|thumb|A fundraising event in 1890 for the construction of the Monument-National]] The '''Monument-National''' is a historic Canadian theatre located at 1182 [[Saint Laurent Boulevard]] in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]]. Erected between 1891 and 1894, it was originally the cultural centre of the [[Saint-Jean-Baptiste Society]].
The building was designed by [[Maurice Perrault]], [[Albert Mesnard]] and [[Joseph Venne]] in the [[Renaissance Revival architecture|Renaissance Revival style]] and utilizes a steel frame—a building technique that was innovative for its time.<ref name=CRHP1>{{CRHP|7154|Le Monument-National|August 10, 2011}}</ref>
==Yiddish theatre== The first performance of a [[Yiddish]] play was held there in what is now the theatre's Ludger-Duvernay room in the winter of 1896. The Monument-National was a key cultural landmark in [[Historic Jewish Quarter, Montreal|Montreal's historic Jewish quarter]], and it continued to host productions from touring and local Yiddish theatre companies until the 1940s.<ref name="Parks">{{cite web|url=http://www.pc.gc.ca/eng/culture/proj/main/corridor1/corridor2.aspx|title=Boulevard Saint-Laurent: Corridor for Immigration, Business and Development|date=2009-04-15|work=Parks Canada Web site|accessdate=2009-05-31|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605115540/http://www.pc.gc.ca/eng/culture/proj/main/corridor1/corridor2.aspx|archivedate=2011-06-05|df=}}</ref><ref name="NTS">{{cite web|url=http://ent-nts.ca/journal/j25p04_looking.htm|title=Looking Back : Monumental|date=Spring 2004|work=National Theatre School of Canada Web site|accessdate=2009-05-31|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090925004343/http://ent-nts.ca/journal/j25p04_looking.htm|archivedate=2009-09-25|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://imjm.ca/location/1364 | title=Interactive Museum of Jewish Montreal |accessdate=January 7, 2013}}</ref>
==Renovations and current status== The theatre was declared a historic monument by the [[Ministère des Affaires culturelles du Québec]] in 1976,<ref name=CRHP1/> and a [[National Historic Sites of Canada|National Historic Site of Canada]] in 1985.<ref>{{CRHP|14663|Monument National National Historic Site of Canada|August 10, 2011}}</ref>
A major restoration project of the theatre was completed in June 1993, in time for the theatre's centennial celebration. The 1,620-seat theatre has been owned by the [[National Theatre School of Canada]] since 1971, and it is the venue used for its productions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thecanadianencyclopedia.com/index.cfm?PgNm=TCE&Params=U1ARTU0002439|title=Monument national|work=[[The Canadian Encyclopedia]]|author=[[Gilles Potvin]]}}</ref>
